The Losers Remain Challengers
HARARE: Before this month's presidential elections, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they got terror.
In the two years that led up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were subjected to intimidation, harassment, and threats from Robert Mugabe's party, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terror is the responsibility of the scoundrels among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
The consequence of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in large parts of the rural areas at all.
In addition, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations in total, I believe that more than 360,000 people in Harare and Chitungwiza stood in line without being able to put their ballot into the ballot box.
I still question the legitimacy of the election result because Mugabe's militias have prevented MDC election observers from being deployed at 52% of rural polling stations.
At the end of the voting process, our party was missing observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in rural areas.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to enforce their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling an exhaustive list of all polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
Even in this early stage of our investigation, a systematic approach has become apparent: in these polling stations, most votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential election, in which the incumbent president, Robert Mugabe, emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is considered illegitimate in their eyes.
The people of Zimbabwe have been denied their right to freely and democratically choose their president.
The dispute over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and deserve to be recognized for it.
Perhaps it is still not too late.
I am writing this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and see the path through with them.
Perhaps the government will arrest me.
I was already arrested on charges of treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never break the will of the people, their rights, and their power to reclaim.
It is in our hands to bring about a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow ourselves to be overwhelmed by desperation.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be prepared to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to finish what we have started together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who did not let themselves be chased away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard in the world.
We have gone through a very rocky path together to achieve democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely had to endure such violence and still understood how to maintain kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply leave these elections, but they must also not fall into the provocation of Mugabe and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that in all of Africa, voters are deceived during elections.
Irregularities, cheating, and fraud seem to be the order of the day in most African states.
There is always a crisis somewhere in Africa related to elections.
It's sad, but the whole continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it's time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Simbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
No time is left to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in their greatest hour of need.
I vow not to leave it.
